    "contents" : "---\ntitle: \"HIV mutants\"\nauthor: \"M. Whitlock\"\ndate: \"7/1/2018\"\noutput: html_document\n---\n\n```{r setup, include=FALSE}\nknitr::opts_chunk$set(echo = TRUE)\nlibrary(boot)\nlibrary(dplyr)\nlibrary(ggplot2)\nlibrary(\"stringr\", lib.loc=\"/Library/Frameworks/R.framework/Versions/3.3/Resources/library\")\n```\n\n## HIV mutant fitness\n\nThe fitness ( and selection coefficient) of dozens of HV mutations were measured in vivo.\n\nTheys et al. 2018\n\n### Reference and data source\n\nTheys K, Feder AF, Gelbart M, Hartl M, Stern A, Pennings PS (2018) Within-patient mutation frequencies reveal fitness costs of CpG dinucleotides and drastic amino acid changes in HIV. *PLoS Genet* 14(6): e1007420. https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pgen.1007420\n\nData from <https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pgen.1007420.s001>\nhttps://journals.plos.org/plosgenetics/article/file?id=10.1371/journal.pgen.1007420.s012&type=supplementary\n\nBacheler(?) data set\n\n### Description\n\nThe HIV virus is an RNA virus, meaning that it stores its genetic material using RNA, rather than DNA. In general RNA viruses have much higher mutation rates than organisms that use DNA. Many of the mutations that appear are harmful to the virus itself, making mutated viruses less able to replicate. Theys et al (2018) measured the decline in fitness of HIV viruses after mutation. They also were able to identify for each mutant whether it changed the amino acid coded for, and if so, whether that change was to a new amino acid which had biochemical properties much different from the unmutated strain. From  \n\nThey also were able to identify for each mutant whether it changed the amino acid in a protein (these are called ÔÇťnon-synonymousÔÇŁ changes), or whether it did not change any amino acid. The latter ÔÇťsynonymousÔÇŁ changes should have little effect on replication rate, while the non-synonymous changes have the potential to cause larger changes in the replication rate of the virus.\n\n\n\n### Possible questions\n\n* Log-transform\n    + not extremely normal but close enough  \n    + good example of how Shapiro-Wilk says not normal, but plenty normal ( on log-transform scale)\n* s of syn vs nonsyn\n* s of different genes\n* s of syn, nonsyn-minor, nonsyn-major  --Anova +Tukey\n\n\n\n### Data\n```{r}\nHIVData <- read.csv(\"///Users/whitlock/Desktop/ Get to Work!/Stats Book/3rd edition/new examples/HIV mutant fitness/HIVmutantFitness.csv\")\nHIVData$type = as.factor(paste(HIVData$TypeOfSite,HIVData$bigAAChange, sep=\"_\"))\nsummary(HIVData)\n```\nnum: an index\nMeanFreq:  observed frequency of mutation in data (used to infer selection coefficient)\nTypeOfSite: \n    nonsyn:  Nonsynonymous mutation that changes teh amino acid; \n    syn: synonymous mutation ( does not change amino acid of codon); \n    overlap: in region of overlap between two genes -- affects sequence of both protiens\n    res: known to create drug resistance\n    stop:  creates stop codon\nWTnt: nucleotide in wild type\nTSmutrate: mutation rate for WT nucleotide\nEstSelCoeff:  estiamted selection coeffiicent ( i.e., proportional reduction in fitness compared to wild type)\nWTAA: amino acid in wilf type\nMUTAA: amino acid in mutant\nbigAAChange: 1 if causes large biochemical change in mutant from wild type\nProRT: which gene?  pro or reverse transcriptase (RT)\nAAnum:  location in gene\n\n## Shapes of distribution\nSelection coefficients are bimodal  and not very well normalized by log-transformation\n\n\n```{r}\nhist(HIVData$EstSelCoeff)\nhist(log(HIVData$EstSelCoeff))\nshapiro.test(log(HIVData$EstSelCoeff))\n\n```\nThe data is not normal by Shapiro-Wilk, but it will be plenty fine for e.g. t-test because of large sample.\n\n## Shapes by Syn vs NonSyn\nLet's look at the shapes of the distributions for synonymous vs. non-synonymous, with hopes of doing a comparisons of mean selection coefffiient between the two types.\n```{r}\nsynonymousSelCoeff = filter(HIVData,TypeOfSite==\"syn\")$EstSelCoeff\nhist(synonymousSelCoeff)\nhist(log(synonymousSelCoeff))\n\n\n\n```\nBeauty!\n\nPulling out only the synonymous and nonsynonymous, and breaking the latter into major and minor AA changes. Also filtering for non-lethals,a nd using only RT data.\n```{r}\nsynNonsynData1=filter(HIVData,str_detect(type, 'syn'))\nsynNonsynData2=filter(synNonsynData1,ProRT==\"RT\")\nsynNonsynData=filter(synNonsynData2,log(EstSelCoeff)<0)\n\n\nggplot(synNonsynData, aes(x = log(EstSelCoeff))) +   \n  geom_histogram(bins=20) + \n  facet_wrap(~ type, ncol = 1)\n\nsynNonsyn_by_type <- group_by(synNonsynData,type)\n\nsummarise(synNonsyn_by_type, group_mean = mean(log(EstSelCoeff), na.rm=TRUE), group_sd = sd(log(EstSelCoeff), na.rm=TRUE))\n\nHIVANOVA <- lm(EstSelCoeff ~ type, data = synNonsynData)\n\nanova(HIVANOVA)\n\nTukeyHSD(aov(HIVANOVA))\n\nwrite.csv(synNonsynData,\"///Users/whitlock/Desktop/ Get to Work!/Stats Book/3rd edition/new examples/HIV mutant fitness/chap15q00SynVsNonsyn.csv\")\n\n```\n\nFor the non-syn sites:\n```{r}\nnonsynonymousSelCoeff = filter(HIVData,TypeOfSite==\"nonsyn\")$EstSelCoeff\nhist(nonsynonymousSelCoeff)\nhist(log(nonsynonymousSelCoeff))\n```\nNot quite as nice.\n\n\nComparing the two:\n```{r}\nmean(log(synonymousSelCoeff))\nmean(log(nonsynonymousSelCoeff))\nvar(log(synonymousSelCoeff))\nvar(log(nonsynonymousSelCoeff))\nsqrt(var(log(synonymousSelCoeff)))\nsqrt(var(log(nonsynonymousSelCoeff)))\nlength(log(synonymousSelCoeff))\nlength(log(nonsynonymousSelCoeff))\nt.test(log(synonymousSelCoeff),log(nonsynonymousSelCoeff))\nt.test(log(synonymousSelCoeff),log(nonsynonymousSelCoeff),var.equal=TRUE)\n```\n## Differences between proteins\nThe study was composed of data fom two different genes, *RT* (reverse transciptase) and *pol*. \n\n```{r}\nPROnonsynSelCoeff = filter(HIVData,ProRT ==\"Pro\", TypeOfSite==\"nonsyn\")$EstSelCoeff\nRTnonsynSelCoeff = filter(HIVData,ProRT ==\"RT\", TypeOfSite==\"nonsyn\")$EstSelCoeff\nhist((PROnonsynSelCoeff))\nhist((RTnonsynSelCoeff))\nhist(log(PROnonsynSelCoeff))\nhist(log(RTnonsynSelCoeff))\nc(mean(log(PROnonsynSelCoeff)),sqrt(var(log(PROnonsynSelCoeff))),length(PROnonsynSelCoeff))\nc(mean(log(RTnonsynSelCoeff)),sqrt(var(log(RTnonsynSelCoeff))),length(RTnonsynSelCoeff))\nt.test(log(PROnonsynSelCoeff),log(RTnonsynSelCoeff))\nt.test(log(PROnonsynSelCoeff),log(RTnonsynSelCoeff),var.equal=TRUE)\n```\n\n\n##  Standard error of mean and median\n Exploring whether there are interesting patterns in the median versus the mean, for the EstSelCoeff\n \n First, the distribution is skewed:\n \n```{r}\n hist(HIVData$EstSelCoeff)\n```\n \n bootstrap SE of the median:\n```{r}\n sampledSelCoeff = sample(HIVData$EstSelCoeff, size = 100)\n boot.median <- function(x, i){ median(x[i]) }\n boot(data=sampledSelCoeff, statistic = boot.median, R = 1000)\n```\n \n bootstrap of the mean\n```{r}\n boot.mean <- function(x, i){ mean(x[i]) }\n boot(data=sampledSelCoeff, statistic = boot.mean, R = 1000)\n```\n \n \n##  Standard error of mean and median## Making a ggplot graph for figure in problem 33 chapter 13\n \n```{r}\n library(ggplot2)\n library(\"gridExtra\", lib.loc=\"/Library/Frameworks/R.framework/Versions/3.3/Resources/library\")\n\n PROnonsynSelCoeffDF = filter(HIVData,ProRT ==\"Pro\", TypeOfSite==\"nonsyn\")\n RTnonsynSelCoeffDF = filter(HIVData,ProRT ==\"RT\", TypeOfSite==\"nonsyn\")\n p1= ggplot(PROnonsynSelCoeffDF, aes(x=EstSelCoeff)) +\n  geom_histogram(bins=10) + labs (x= \"Reduction in replication PRO\", y=\"Frequency\" ) +\n   theme_classic() \n \n p2= ggplot(RTnonsynSelCoeffDF, aes(x=EstSelCoeff)) +\n   geom_histogram(bins=10) + labs (x= \"Reduction in replication RT\", y=\"Frequency\" ) +\n   theme_classic() + coord_fixed(ratio = 3/4)\np3= ggplot(PROnonsynSelCoeffDF, aes(x=log(EstSelCoeff))) +\n  geom_histogram(bins=10) + labs (x= \"Log reduction in replication PRO\", y=\"Frequency\" ) +\n  theme_classic()\n p4= ggplot(RTnonsynSelCoeffDF, aes(x=log(EstSelCoeff))) +\n   geom_histogram(bins=10)  + labs (x= \"Log reduction in replication RT\", y=\"Frequency\" ) +\n   theme_classic()\n   \n   grid.arrange(p1, p2, p3, p4, nrow=2)\n```\n ",
